Consistency was the plan today.  Time on my feet & that's what we did. 

This was not an easy run for me. I didn't run much this week and I felt that.  But my hammy us still tight and I'm working hard to help that heal but also be consistent and make sure I'm not losing what I've built the last 5 months since Cleveland Marathon. 

I felt it all tonight.  But I'm not in pain. And the hamstring does not feel any worse. I tried to keep flat on this. I thought I did pretty well but the elevation today in 16 miles is almost double the elevation of the entire Chicago Marathon. 

My pace is slower.  My stride is still off. But I consistently held pace, felt good overall and feel genuinely positive about running a good marathon in 3ish weeks! 

LFG.

@risereigntraining @jillian_risereign

Keep watching to see dry needling and electrodes in action! It really is so cool how this works!! If needles bother you, you may not want to watch, just as a heads up, you'll just see them in but not going in. ✨️

When something felt off 10 days ago in my hamstring and I knew I needed to act fast, prevent a significant injury and get to the @chimarathon healthy. @myedgept was ready to help immediately. Getting me to the start line ready to race AND hit my goals with a shorter time frame to overcome this hamstring issue meant having interventions and time with Dr Nick to get me right where I need to be. 

I'm feeling good. I have a great PT and a great running coach, @jillian_risereign . I'm optimistic! 

I know many will ask- the dry needling did not hurt. You can feel it. You can definitely feel the electrodes.  It's meant to be felt, from my understanding but it was not painful and I'll be back next Monday again!  My entire appointment took about 30 minutes so it's a lot of gain for a short amount of time.  Invest in yourself and your training and  I'll always stand by that!  We are better athletes when we have the right supports in place! 

Thanks again, Dr Nick @myedgept -for also believing that I can do this & letting me document it here too!!! ⚡️🌟🪽🏃‍♀️

I had some marathon pace work in this  run today.  I figured I'd see how my hamstring did and go from there. I feel great running my warm up, cool down paces.  When my cadence gets faster and my stride gets longer is when I notice that tightness now in the hamstring so I just figured I'd see where it is and adjust.  I ran the 1/3 quicker and then slowed for 2/3 and 3/3.  I was still in my pace range but steadier on my feet slightly slower. 

This run gave me the confidence that I really needed right now considering I haven't done a lot the last two weeks, especially any pace work.  It's in there,  I've trained for it. But, getting to the start line ( healthy with strong legs) at @chimarathon is the goal right now and we will keep making adjustments to make sure that happens. 

Overall, I'm absolutely seeing improvement in the hamstring. But there's a delicate balance to keep as well. 

Happy with this one. 💓🪽🏃‍♀️

Dr Nick- @myedgept THANK YOU!!!!! I cannot say it enough.  In sheer moments of panic weeks before my huge race you assured me we could get through pain in a hamstring and do what we could to get it where it needs to be- or give it our best shot trying.  We didn't have a ton of time for it to heal and also had to keep it from getting really hurt while I continued training. 

I finished my last PT session today and now, all that is left to do is run the CHICAGO MARATHON @chimarathon in 9 days!! 

There's so much more to being a runner than just running. We ask so much of our bodies and we train so hard- making sure we have the injury prevention down or interventions in place to help us stay healthy & doing what we love. Thank you @risereigntraining for knowing I needed more help with this! 

There's so much more out there to PT than just foam rolling and stretching with bands.  My mind was blown in just 3 weeks...& now it's time to shine! 🌞

Thanks for listening to me ramble about running, goals, kids, sports and whatever else over the last couple weeks. 

Friends, be open to getting help. Don't suffer alone or keep lifting or running injured because you don't/ can't stop with training. Get help. And, if you're local, GO SEE DR. NICK!

I'm baaaaaaaack! 🏃‍♀️🎉

Oooooh. I so needed this run today. 8 days post marathon and it was a good break. After Chicago I spent quite a bit of time wallowing in how my hamstring felt. It still isn't 100% but it is better after not running at all over the last week. 

It's a light return this week and I'm still going to be able to pace the Youngstown Half Marathon this coming weekend and then the following week I'll have my plastic surgery.  I'm not sure how long I'll be down from that yet. My surgeon said with my level of fitness, maybe 4 weeks depending on healing at that point.  I'm hopeful for that, I generally heal well. But, I understand the need to heal as well. So. We will see. 

I expect my hamstring will fully heal during that time and I'll be ready to jump back into a spring training block for a spring marathon! 🎉🏃‍♀️

So happy to get out there today ( cold, slightly rainy) and loved every second. My legs and lungs just wanted to GO! 😤💜

When I say I swell, I swell. 🤣 

Today, I'm feeling a lot more like myself.  The water I'm retaining is subsiding. Some of the swelling will remain for me for weeks, if not months, especially by the evening. That's part of the process with plastic surgery.  I think sometimes before and after pictures simply show a quick snapshot of that but we quickly forget how hard healing is and months and months of getting back to normal. Or. Learning our new normal with a different body. 

For now, I'm just happy to not feel like a blowfish. 

🤣💜

3 week update. ✂️

Incision is healing well. Minus a small opening in the armpit ( I say opening lightly, it's minimal but still a high tension area)  someone asked last time about the rippled areas around the incision- those all flatten out and it's normal to have those. I had them with my tummy tuck too. 

I feel like an old pro at plastic surgery recovery.  I do know what my body needs, how to take care of the incision and what I need to do... which is a positive! 

It still hurts.  I'm still swollen. Bruised. It's healing but I underestimated this surgery ( unfortunately by a lot). Thankful now to have done it ( I think ) and it will be worth it. I can't wait to run with free arms and how incredible it will be. 💕

Arm lift update because it's been 4 weeks.  I feel so much better.  I can't wait to be 100% back to normal but for right now, I just feel good and my range of motion is coming back.  The opening I have is healing better. There's some spots I'm not completely happy with and will likely lead to a small revision.  But, it happens and arms are tricky with so much excess skin to remove and tuck.  I'll see how it all looks healed and go from there.  The important thing for me right now is getting back to normal.  Normal movement. Normal training.  Normal life.  If I do a revision, It would likely be after spring training/ racing.  Or could even be next fall maybe.  We will see.  I'm not super concerned with it yet. 

 I'm super happy with how it is healing and the incisions and placement.  I couldn't have asked for better.  I do thankfully heal well... maybe it's all that swelling my body does 🤣  I am still pretty swollen actually.  I expect the next couple weeks it will start going down more- I've been told 10% a week reduction in swelling is expected.  So I'd still have 60% to go if we calculate it that way because it's been 4 weeks. 

I even noticed with how busy I was yesterday that my feet/ ankles were swollen.  That hasn't happened since having  weight loss surgery-  other than long runs or long travel days in the car. 

 So, there's my update.  Better but still a long way to go to normal.  I'm hoping about 2 more weeks.  I believe I'll be back to some easy jogging by Dec 9th. 🤞🏻

It's been 5 days. And, I've had a lot of questions about the dog attack and have not been able to get to all of them. 

I was a half mile from my house when a large breed dog attacked me while outside with his owner.  I was chased down, lunged at, growled at, jumped on, almost knocked down and  bit twice before the owner caught the dog by his collar to pull him off of me.  I fully believe he was trying to bite my neck and face area and I had to block him with my shoulders and arm. 

I was in the road. Running home.  I stopped.  I told him no. I forgot my mace and had no other way to protect myself.  The dog  did not listen to the owners commands to stop. And, he attacked me. 

He is the same dog who chased me down, with similar behavior over the summer and the owners apologized then but he didn't bite me then. 

 If you watch the video, they have decided to euthanize him. And, of course, I have mixed feelings about that too but, my safety and the safety of others ( including my children who ride their bikes on our road) is the priority here. 

I hope it doesn't scar too bad on my brand new skinny arms.  But, the emotional and mental part of being attacked by a dog, doing what I love, will far outlast the physical marks on my arm. 

Glad it wasn't worse. Still really sad it happened. 

Thanks for the love this week. 

🩷

It's been almost 11 weeks since my brachioplasty ( arm lift) surgery. 

I've gone through many scar treatments over the years with previous surgeries and recently recieved @wearenokori and I am LOVING it so far.  I cannot wait to see how my incisions look in the coming weeks and months. 

I'm using tape on my arms still & the balm on the breast lift scars.  The balm is so, so smooth!  I love that the tape line is skinnier than other brands and it  has kept it from rolling up like others! 

 I'll be sure to post some updates because I know scar treatment is a HUGE deal for those of us having plastics. 

I'll also be adding the balm onto the dog bite marks when I'm allowed by the doctor!

Moving back into a routine after the last several months of (what I'd say were) setbacks. But, I feel GREAT💪

Since October, I had surgery, recovered, dealt with significant back pain from being sedentary for so long, Covid then a dog bite! 

You know the great thing about people? We are resilient.  If you've dealt with something, you can come back from that. You have to want to. You have to put in the work. You have to understand you cannot start back at the level you once were- BUT- know it will come back. 

I'm zeroed in on my 6th marathon in 106 days!🏃‍♀️🏃‍♀️🏃‍♀️

@jillian_risereign will take care of my training block and, quite frankly, having a coach makes ALL the difference!!! I'm strength training twice a week for sports performance. Cross training.  I'M PUMPED. 💪

While I'm a running coach & personal trainer- I'm also a marathon runner myself!!! 🩷🩷🩷
